Equation (17) specifies:
- If a new detection $ d_{\text{new}} $ does not overlap with any existing detection $ d_{\text{exist}} $ (using predicate $ \phi $), then it is simply added: $ D \cup \{d_{\text{new}}\} $.
- If there is overlap, then the two detections are fused using the fusion operation $ F $, which replaces the existing detection with the fused result (as defined in Equations 13–14).

This means the new retained detections are **not** added without modification (eliminating option A), nor are they replacing the entire set (eliminating option B). Instead, they are merged with the existing detections using a conditional fusion strategy based on spatial-temporal overlap (eliminating option C, which mentions symmetric difference). The new detections are filtered based on overlap with existing detections before being incorporated (option D).

Thus, the correct interpretation is that the new retained detections are filtered based on the existing detections before being added.

