> FNMR(σ) = |{IS ∈ I_low-quality | Q(IS) ≥ σ}| / |{IS | Q(IS) ≥ σ}|

This means FNMR measures the rate at which the surrogate model Q incorrectly accepts low-quality samples (i.e., “non-matches” are wrongly classified as matches). This corresponds to option B and C, since both mention incorrect acceptance of low-quality samples.

Additionally, the text describes how FNMR is evaluated by sweeping σ across its range. As σ increases, the threshold for accepting samples becomes higher, meaning fewer samples (including low-quality ones) will meet the condition Q(IS) ≥ σ. Therefore, the number of incorrectly accepted low-quality samples (FNMR) should decrease as σ increases.

Thus, the correct answer is:

**C. FNMR measures the rate at which low-quality samples are incorrectly accepted; it decreases as σ increases.**

