   $$
   (Chunk 20). This means $\mathcal{R}_{ed}$ is the square root of $\mathcal{R}_{cs}$, implying a monotonic relationship where higher $\mathcal{R}_{cs}$ corresponds to higher $\mathcal{R}_{ed}$, but they are not numerically equivalent.

4. Additionally, the paper notes that although $\mathcal{R}_{ed}$ and $\mathcal{R}_{cs}$ are mathematically related via this transformation, they are treated as equivalent in practice for experimental simplicity (Chunk 20).

5. However, neither metric satisfies the “worst-robustness” property (Chunk 15, Chunk 17), and their equivalence under unit-length embeddings is not claimed — rather, the relationship is explicitly defined via the square root transformation.

