> $$ M_{\text{iou\_overlap}} = \frac{1}{N_{\text{pairs}}} \sum_{p<q} \text{IoU}(B_p, B_q) $$
> 
> where $ N_{\text{pairs}} = \binom{N_{\text{bboxes}}}{2} = \frac{N_{\text{bboxes}}(N_{\text{bboxes}} - 1)}{2} $

This means that as the number of bounding boxes $ N_{\text{bboxes}} $ increases, the denominator $ N_{\text{pairs}} $ grows quadratically ($ O(N^2) $), while the numerator is the sum of all pairwise IoU values.

However, the key point is that the mean pairwise overlap is **not** simply an average over fixed-sized bins—it is normalized by the number of pairs. Therefore, even if the total sum of IoUs increases with more boxes, the normalization ensures that the mean is computed per pair, making it invariant to the number of boxes *in principle*. But in practice, the mean can still be affected by the distribution of IoU values.

But note: the question asks how $ M_{\text{iou\_overlap}} $ changes as the number of bounding boxes increases. If we assume that the distribution of IoU values remains consistent (e.g., the average IoU per pair doesn't change), then increasing the number of boxes would not change the mean pairwise overlap—because the formula normalizes by the number of pairs.

However, in real-world scenarios, adding more boxes often leads to more overlapping instances (especially in crowded scenes), which could cause the mean IoU to decrease due to dilution by many low-overlap pairs. But the formula itself does not inherently depend on the number of boxes—it only depends on the sum of IoUs divided by the number of pairs.

